description.para: These types and macros provide the equivalent of 32- and 64-bit integer types from C99 headers stdint.h and inttypes.h. These headers are also there in C++11. The types and macros from here should be used instead of int32_t etc.
(MSVC 2015 still doesn't support the format strings.)

briefdescription.para: Keyword to use in C code instead of C99 inline.

detaileddescription.para: Some of the C compilers we support do not recognize the C99 keyword inline. This macro should be used in C code and in shared C/C++ headers to indicate a function is inlined. C++ code should use plain inline, as that is already in C++98.

briefdescription.para: Keyword to use in instead of C99 restrict.

detaileddescription.para: We cannot use restrict because it is only in C99, but not in C++. This macro should instead be used to allow easily supporting different compilers.

briefdescription.para: Defined to 1 when compiling as C++11.

detaileddescription.para: While GROMACS only supports C++11 compilation, there are some parts of the code that are compiled with other tools than the actual C++ compiler, and these may not support C++11. Most notable such case is all of CUDA code (with CUDA versions older than 6.5), but other types of kernels might also have similar limitations in the future.

The define is intended for conditional compilation in low-level headers that need to support inclusion from such non-C++11 files, but get significant benefit (e.g., for correctness checking or more convenient use) from C++11. It should only be used for features that do not influence the ABI of the header; e.g., static_asserts or additional helper methods.

briefdescription.para: Attribute to suppress compiler warnings about unused function parameters.

detaileddescription.para: This attribute suppresses compiler warnings about unused function arguments by marking them as possibly unused. Some arguments are unused but have to be retained to preserve a function signature that must match that of another function. Some arguments are only used in some conditional compilation code paths (e.g. MPI).

briefdescription.para: Indicate that a function is not expected to return.
C++11 constexpr everywhere except MSVC 2013, where it is empty.

detaileddescription.para: Support for constexpr was not added until MSVC 2015, and it still seems to be unreliable. Since interacting with parts of libc++ and libstdc++ depend on it (for instance the min/max calls in our random engines), we need to specify it for other compilers.

type
Type of variable
alignment
Alignment in multiples of type
Typical usage: GMX_ALIGNED(real,GMX_SIMD_REAL_WIDTH)buf[...];

briefdescription.para: Macro to explicitly ignore an unused value.
Macro to explicitly ignore a return value of a call.

detaileddescription.para: Mainly meant for ignoring values of functions declared with __attribute__((warn_unused_return)). Makes it easy to find those places if they need to be fixed, and document the intent in cases where the return value really can be ignored. It also makes it easy to adapt the approach so that they don't produce warnings. A cast to void doesn't remove the warning in gcc, while adding a dummy variable can cause warnings about an unused variable.

briefdescription.para: Boolean type for use in GROMACS C code.

detaileddescription.para: There is no standard size for 'bool' in C++, so when we previously defined it to int for C code the data types (and structs) would have different size depending on your compiler, both at GROMACS build time and when you use the library. The only way around this is to NOT assume anything about the C++ type, so we cannot use the name 'bool' in our C code anymore.
